  "prompt": "How many stars in the sky?",
  "response": "The number of stars in the observable universe is estimated to be around 100 billion to 200 billion galaxies, each containing an average of 100 billion stars. This results in an estimate of roughly 10^22 to 10^24 stars, or 10 sextillion to 1 septillion stars. However, the exact number is difficult to determine, and many stars remain uncounted or undiscovered. In the night sky, under ideal conditions, the unaided eye can see about 2,500 to 3,000 stars at any given time.",
